This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with language generation and communication. The paper proposes a new model called CopyNet for sequence-to-sequence learning that incorporates a copying mechanism, which is relevant to natural language processing. Additionally, the paper also mentions text summarization tasks, which is a common application of language generation. 

The paper also involves the use of neural networks, which is a common technique in machine learning and falls under the sub-categories of cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). 

Furthermore, the paper's focus on sequence-to-sequence learning and the use of RNN-based models suggests that it could also belong to the sub-category of cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). 

Finally, the paper's mention of real-world datasets and the potential application of CopyNet in computer vision tasks suggests that it could also belong to the sub-category of cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition).
